[[Category:Medieval architecture]]
[[Category:Benedictine monasteries in France]]
[[Category:Monuments historiques of Côte-d'Or]]

'''Comedia suelta''' or simply '''suelta''' (From Spanish '[[wikt:suelto|suelto]]', "loose", "separate") was a practice of printing plays as a separate edition, often simpler than that of a book with collection of plays: cheaper paper, no binding, no cover sheet, ets. The practice was popular since early 16th century onwards. It was similar to the English practice of ''[[quarto]]'' prints popular since the [[Elizabethan era]].<ref>[http://teatrosiglodeoro.bne.es/DocumentosPdf/31877/031877.pdf Some Problems Posed by ''Suelta'' Editions of Plays], Don W. CruickShank</ref><ref>"The Comedia Suelta: History of a Format", Edward M. Wilson</ref><ref>Margarita Vazques Estevez, "Comedias sueltas del 'Institut de Teatre' en Barcelona", Edition Reichenberger, 1987, {{ISBN|3-923593-46-5}}, 220pp., [https://books.google.com/books?id=XkQRg-DFhvUC&pg=PA7&dq=suelta+print&hl=en&ei=QmjiTrDGLsqqiAK-jd2pBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CHUQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=suelta%20print&f=false p. 7, Introduction]</ref>
