{{Infobox anatomy
| Name = Intermammary cleft
| Latin = sulcus intermammarius
| Image = Weibliche-brust.jpg
| Caption = Anatomical region of woman's cleavage
}}

In female [[Human body|human anatomy]], the '''intermammary cleft''' or '''intermammary sulcus''' or '''sulcus intermammarius''' of a woman is delineated by where the fatty portions of each breast sits in relationship to the [[sternum]] (or breastbone).<ref name ="  scoop">Dr. Ted Eisenberg and Joyce K. Eisenberg, ‘’ The Scoop on Breasts: A Plastic Surgeon Busts the Myths’’, Incompra Press, 2012, {{ISBN|978-0-9857249-3-1}}</ref> It divides the two mammary complexes that consist of two bodies of fatty pads, glandular tissues of [[mammary gland]]s, connective tissues, and skin, as well as two duct systems ([[lactiferous duct]] of [[lymphatic vessel]]) and [[lobule]] [[alveoli]] emanating from two [[nipple]]s.<ref>Heide Schatten and Gheorghe M. Constantinescu, ''Comparative Reproductive Biology'', page 17, John Wiley & Sons, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-470-39025-2}}</ref><ref>Genaro Andres Contreras, ''The Use of Tylosin to Treat Intramammary Infections '', page 22, ProQuest, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-549-60762-5}}</ref> Lymph vessels can [[ventral]]ly extend as far as the intermammary sulcus.<ref>Charles Wesley Turner, ''The mammary gland'' (vol. 1), page 80, Lucas Bros., 1952</ref>

== Anatomy ==
{{Annotated image
|  image       =  Superficial anatomy (unnoted).png
